Are you getting in your own way? I was talking with one of my clients this weekend about binge eating & how hard it can be to stick to your diet. You promise yourself you will change, yet you continuously quit. It hurts. But you keep doing it.

Self sabotage is a behavior and for most of us it’s a habit. When you feel the urge to self sabotage, stop & ask yourself what am I feeling in this moment that I don’t want to? 

Get out of your comfort zone. End that toxic relationship. Quit that toxic job. Start addressing how you feel.

You deserve the best & you deserve to FEEL your best. 🤍

Little physique & baby bump update 💖 I’m 11 weeks & baby is the size of a strawberry. Fingers crossed I’m past the morning sickness, & thankfully I didn’t experience much of it. My appetite is never ending, it’s been burgers or mexican food. Mentally it’s been hard not eating as healthy as I’m used to, but I’m thankful to still have an appetite. I’ve felt extremely tired making it even harder to find the motivation to work out. BUT I do feel like things are looking up, my energy is back, I have more control of my appetite, and I’m excited to follow my new pregnancy workout plan! To all my moms to be, give your body grace & be kind to yourself, we only get 9 months of this, enjoy it. 🥹

Foods I ENJOYED in Miami with no guilt. During my first trimester it’s been harder to eat “clean” or healthy like I’m used to. In the past I would of never been able to go on vacation & not worry about “macros” or how many carbs I’ve ate 🥴 now I’m eating to fuel my body & enjoying foods that sound good!

Rule 1: I always try to eat the protein from my meals first 
Rule 2: I always enjoy a glass of water before my meal comes to prevent over eating

You can still be about “fitness” and enjoy yourself while on vacation. Life is short. Vacation is even shorter. The gym will always be there for you!

Just like that the first trimester is over 🥹 I would be lying if I said embracing the rapid changes of pregnancy is easy. Don’t get me wrong I am so excited to be expanding our family, but what you can’t prepare for is how much your body will change mentally and physically. Here are 3 things I’ve had to learn to accept while being pregnant ⬇️

1. Weight gain. Bye bye 6 pack! The number on the scale has gone up and some days it get to me, but I know I’m growing a healthy baby.
2. My meal prep has not been appetizing. Heating up my chicken and veggies made me so nauseous. Most days it was chipotle or pizza. Mentally it was hard to not be eating as “clean” as I’d like. 
3. My workout motivation was not what it used to be. I constantly felt tired and wanted to nap instead of working out. I’m winded easily and take longer rest. 

Going into my second trimester I can already feel my energy levels are higher and I have control of my appetite. Excited to be following my new Fit 4 Pregnancy program coming to @bodybybaybabes soon 💪🏼

MY FITNESS JOURNEY 💪🏼 I grew up super active, always doing sports and my moms Billy Banks Tae Bo workouts. Boys in middle school would make fun of my muscular arms. I went on to be a competitive cheerleader for 10+ years and after that career ended in college I felt lost.

I became a cardio bunny, obsessed with the number on the scale and always doing fasted cardio. I wanted to be the smallest version of myself, 116lbs to be exact. 

Upon graduating from college I started working with a coach. I went on to compete in 2 bodybuilding shows and a handful of powerlifting competitions. I felt like an athlete again but it took a toll on the body both mentally & physically. Weighed 122lbs on stage. 

2020 comes around, gyms shut down, as a personal trainer, not only did I have to maneuver my career, I had to manage my own physical health. I opened my own gym, addressed my body dysmorphia, focused on weight gain and creating a healthy relationship with food. Weight fluctuating between 128-132lbs.

Currently, 13 weeks pregnant. Eating when I’m hungry. Even in the middle of the night. Working out and honoring my body. 135lbs & happy.

Two things you should focus on training while pregnant is your core & pelvic floor. First off, while lifting weights you should ALWAYS be engaging your core. If you cannot properly engage it during an exercise try decreasing the weight & focus on your form. The 3 Exercises I Performed in this Video are… ⬇️

1. 90/90 kneeling squats w/ inner core breaths: as you come onto the knees & squeeze the hips forward you let out an exhale deep from within your diaphragm & engage the inner core 
2. Modified Side Plank: focus on the side obliques and lifting your hip towards the ceiling 
3. Basic Diaphragmatic Breathing: keeping the chest still, inhale filling the belly up, exhale drawing the rib cage towards the floor.

Hoping all my pregnancy gains go to my glutes 😛🍑 currently 26 weeks pregnant & these are 3 staples exercises that I am still doing weekly. I’m lifting at about 50% of my max weight to ensure I’m able to engage my core and not strain my body. Always LISTEN to your body 💪🏼 details below ⬇️

1. Banded lateral kickbacks: toe is turned outward & instead of kicking straight back we are kind of kicking at an angle. Brace your upper body against the wall and don’t allow it to move.

2. Barbell Sumo Deadlifts: can also be modified and done with dumbbells. This is a bigger compound movement so you want to make sure your core is always engaged.

3. Lateral Step Ups: stepping up on the side of the box is more comfortable since my belly is growing. I feel confident with this box height but again always modify it to what feels best/safest for YOU.

Ingredients:
1 cup of Strawberries 
1/2 cup plain yogurt
1 tsp vanilla stevia sweetener 
1 cup of dark chocolate chips 
1 tsp coconut oil 

Directions:
1. Add diced strawberries to a bowl. Stir in the yogurt + vanilla sweetener. Mix until strawberries are well coated.
2. Add small scoops of strawberry mixture onto parchment paper lined baking sheet.
3. Place clusters in the freezer for 45 minutes.
4. To make the chocolate mix, add chocolate chips into bowl & melt for roughly 30 seconds, stirring until chocolate is smooth. Let’s chocolate cool for about 5 minutes so it doesn’t melt yogurt. 
5. Remove frozen clusters from freezer. Dip each cluster into the chocolate & place back on baking sheet. The chocolate will harden. 
6. Enjoy right away or store in the fridge for later.

3. Dip in Paleo breadcrumbs coating both sides.
4. Dip in Franks Red Hot buffalo sauce.
5. Place in air fryer at 390 for 4 minutes.
6. Rotate the chicken and cook for an additional 2-4 minutes

The Wrap:
1. Low carb tortilla, with lettuce, tomato’s, crushed croutons, and chicken.

3. Add blue cheese crumbles or pepper Jack cheese for extra zest.
4. ENJOY 😋

Left: the day I found out I was pregnant 🤰🏼 Right: 38 weeks pregnant 

Let me start off by saying pregnancy is NOT a one size fits all. We cannot compare one pregnancy to another. Every BODY is different & I don’t believe in the guidelines set from so called “health professionals” saying pregnant women should only gain __ amount of weight 

Some women may gain majority of their weight first trimester, while others might not see a difference until later on in pregnancy. But again weight gain is NORMAL and HEALTHY for both you & baby. 

I struggled watching the scale go up & up. But I know it’s only natural. I kept the promises I made to myself and that’s my biggest flex. I worked out all 9 months of pregnancy, ate efficiently, while still indulging in cravings here & there. Your body is going to change all you can do is continue to treat it kindly ✨

When people ask me how I’ve stayed motivated to workout throughout my entire pregnancy… it’s called discipline 💪🏼 I’ve been lifting for 10+ years, I don’t rely on motivation to get me to the gym. I have the discipline to exercise, it’s a nonnegotiable if I want to be the healthiest version of myself 🩷

Exercises I Avoided During Pregnancy & Why 👇🏼 this is all personal choice. Everyone is going to have their own opinion & that’s okay. 

1. Planks & any other exercise in a plank position (like push ups) these types of exercises put tons of strain on the abdomen which can contribute to Diastasis Recti 

2. Pull ups: to prevent strain on my abdomen & pelvic floor

3. Barbell Hip Thrust: a very demanding movement, hard on pelvic floor & I did not want to load my pelvis with the weight

4. Chest Supported Exercises: obviously because the belly was in the way 🤰🏼 

5. During My 2-3rd Trimester Any Exercises That Required Me To Lay Flat On My Back: the weight of uterus could restrict major blood vessels

Sweet Potato Nachos, IM OBSESSED. This is currently my favorite dish. It’s quick & easy to make. Hit SAVE & tell me what you think 😋

Ingredients:
2 Large Sweet Potatoes 🍠 
Ground Beef (or Turkey)
Black Beans 
Coconut Oil
Shredded Cheese 🧀 
Avocado 🥑 

Directions:
1. Preheat oven to 425
2. Slice up your sweet potato’s, place on cookie sheet, cover with coconut oil & place in oven for 35-45 minutes or until sweet potatoes are soft.
3. Cook your meat & beans on the stove while the sweet potatoes bake. 
4. Remove from oven & sprinkle with cheese, meat, & beans.
5. Place back into oven @ 325F for 8-10 minutes or until cheese is melted.
6. Top with avocado & hot sauce (other good options would be tomato’s, jalapeños, bacon, cilantro, lettuce etc.)

Diaphragm breathing is a technique postpartum mamas can start doing immediately to accelerate recovery. But what is it? And why should we do it? 

Diaphragmatic Breathing is essentially breathing through your diaphragm - this allows you to start connecting with your abdominal muscles after pregnancy. It has other benefits like reducing heart rate, helps you relax, and increases how much oxygen is in your blood. 

How to do it: 
Laying on your back, place one hand on your stomach & the other on your chest. 
Inhale, expanding your belly. 
Then you will exhale & empty your belly drawing your belly button into your spine.

Core Exercises I did throughout pregnancy & continue to do postpartum. There are many myths & questions including whether or not you should do any prenatal core training. I want to reassure you & let you know it is not just safe, but VERY beneficial, to train your core during pregnancy. Hit Save & Try These Exercises 👇🏼

▫️Diaphragm Breathing - exhale is when you draw the belly button into the spin squeezing the core. Inhale is when you fill your belly up

▫️Chest Ball Squeeze with Breath - inhale full belly up, exhale draw the belly button into spine while squeezing the ball between hands

▫️Inner Thigh Ball Squeeze with Breath - place ball between the knees as you exhale you squeeze the ball and draw the belly button in. As you inhale relax but don’t let the ball drop. 

▫️Overhead Ball Drop With Breath - as you inhale you lift ball overhead, as you exhale you drop the ball straight out in front of you.
